http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Co-founder-of-Pappas-Restaurants-dies-1952087.php



Co-founder of Pappas Restaurants dies
1919 PETE HARRIS PAPPAS 2005A leader in Houston's restaurant scene


By Nicki Britton


        Published 6:30 am, Wednesday, December 21, 2005
    



































































Pete Harris Pappas took risks.
From building a restaurant dynasty to mentoring entrepreneurs and piloting small aircraft, "Mr. Pete," as colleagues and employees called him, was a leader with wide-reaching impact on the Houston hospitality industry.
The co-founder of Pappas Restaurants, a privately held chain of about 80 eateries, including Pappasito's Cantina, Pappadeaux Seafood Kitchen and Pappas Bros. Steakhouse, died Sunday of natural causes at age 86.
Pappas was a leader in the Houston hospitality community for almost 60 years.
"He was very in tune with the restaurant scene," said George Christie, vice president of Christie's Steak and Seafood House and president of the Greater Houston Restaurant Association. "He had the pulse of the business under his thumb."
Pappas Restaurants, in tune with the Texas love of big food, are famous for serving diners with generous portions at affordable prices.






Latest Houston News Video
 
(Story continues below ...)


"(They) put 25 percent more food on your plate. That is their advertising. I have friends who go to Pappas restaurants because they know there is sure to be some food left over that they can take home," Dick Huiras, former president of a restaurant consultant group, told the Chronicle in a previous interview.
Dimitrios Fetokakis, owner of Niko Niko's Greek restaurant, considered Pappas a mentor. "Any time I called Mr. Pete, even when I was a kid, he would pick up the phone and listen."
When Fetokakis's parents opened a restaurant in the mid-1970s, he said, Pappas — a stranger — met with them and agreed to give them some equipment.
"You ask yourself, would you give help to someone you don't know?" said Fetokakis. His parents later repaid Pappas.
"(Pete) comes from a time when character counted," said nephew Chris J. Pappas, who runs Pappas Restaurants with his brother Harris.
"He could read a man's character and know that he was going to put his best efforts in."
Houston was boomtown

Pappas was born in Dallas in 1919, and moved to Houston in 1946 with his three brothers. Their father, a Greek immigrant who owned restaurants in Texas, Arkansas and Tennessee, had alerted them to a business opportunity in Houston distributing refrigeration equipment.

"Houston was an up-and-coming market," said Chris Pappas. "They saw it as a boomtown in the '40s. It was a very open town, an accepting town to people moving here, a wildcat town."
The brothers founded Pappas Refrigeration. Pete Pappas patented several pieces of equipment, including a commercial ice machine still used in the seafood industry.
According to Chris Pappas, the brothers' entrepreneurship led to their success. According to a family friend, he said, the brothers figured out the secret to selling refrigeration equipment: "Follow the ice truck around."
In 1967, Pappas and his brother, Jim, left the equipment business and opened Dot Coffee Shop, followed shortly by the Brisket House, now Pappas Bar-B-Q. Jim Pappas' sons, Chris, Harris and Gregory J. Pappas, now deceased, later joined the business. The family went on to open the Strawberry Patch (later reconceived as Pappas Bros. Steakhouse), Pappas Seafood, Pappasito's, Pappadeaux and Yia Yia Mary's.
Served in Army Air Corps

Pappas stepped down as head of the family company several years ago, but remained active. He was essential to the siting of new restaurants, said Chris Pappas. Until just a few weeks ago, he continued to come to the Pappas Restaurants office on Yale Street.

Pappas served in the Army Air Corps during World War II.
"He served ... with the inspector general's corps," said his nephew. "He would inspect crash accidents."
The job did not deter the recreational pilot, who enjoyed flying small planes to remote hunting areas.
Pappas is remembered by some members of the restaurant community as a quiet but fun-loving leader.
Alex Brennan-Martin, whose family owns Brennan's of Houston and Commander's Palace in New Orleans, described Pappas' contributions to the local restaurant scene as "incalculable.
"People say to me, 'Oh, you're part of the Brennan family,' and I chuckle," he said. "What we've done is minuscule compared to the Pappas (family). I admire them like I admire almost no one else."
Pappas is survived by Helen Lucas Pappas, his wife of 48 years, daughters Pamela Mattingly and Mersina Stubbs, and five grandchildren.
Services will be held at 10:30 a.m. today at the Annunciation Greek Orthodox Cathedral, 3511 Yoakum Blvd. In lieu of flowers, the family requests memorials be directed to The Star of Hope and The Ronald McDonald House.
nicki.britton@chron.com
 














