A new generation takes the reins at Pappas Restaurants

1 / 6


Back to Gallery









 

There are few more recognizable names in Houston than the Pappas family. We've all eaten at one of their restaurants: Pappas Bar-B-Q for smoked meats, Pappadeaux for seafood, and Pappasito's for Tex-Mex just to name a few.
The Pappas empire has grown from two restaurants in downtown Houston in 1967 to more than 85 restaurants in eight states today.
Few Houstonians know the story behind the family that has expanded Pappas Restaurants into one of the country's largest family-owned restaurant chains. It starts in 1897, when H.D. Pappas immigrated to America from Greece. He settled in Dallas and raised four sons - Jim, Pete, Tom and George. The sons moved to Houston in the 1940s to start a successful refrigeration business - a growth industry at the time to say the least.





In addition to refrigeration equipment, the brothers started selling other equipment to local restaurants. They slowly started to get into the restaurant business themselves.
By the 1960s they were concentrating on two of their restaurants in downtown Houston, both on Pierce Street: The Dot Coffee Shop (where the Metro station is now), and the Brisket House (where a Pappas Bar-B-Q still is).





Translator
To read this article in one of Houston's most-spoken languages, click on the button below.








