The best deals of the 2017 Houston Restaurant Weeks









Zero Degrees is expected to infuse Houston's Chinatown with









10 best bets for 2017 Houston Restaurant Weeks









Houston Restaurant Violations, July 12-19









IHOP offering 59-cent pancakes Tuesday




Around that time, Jim's sons returned to Houston - Harris from the Army and Chris from college. Though the family business was successful, the two wanted to strike out on their own. Harris took a job at the Luby's Cafeteria chain. Chris sold bibles door-to-door and later took a job at a Denny's restaurant. 
It was during this time that Harris and Chris learned every aspect of the restaurant business from dish washing to cooking to serving and management. In 1967, they took over day-to-day management of the family restaurants and laid the foundation for the business it is today. Greg Pappas, another brother involved in the family business, died in a car accident in 1995.
Harris and Chris still are directly involved in day-to-day operation of Pappas Restaurants, but, over the past few years, their children have taken on more prominent roles. 
"They live in a world where nothing is ever good enough, nothing is ever completed," says Christina Pappas, referring to standards set by her father, Harris, and uncle, Chris. Like a lot of heirs to Texas food empires, the sense of responsibility (and pressure) to continue the success of the family business is palpable. But the new generation of Pappas family restaurateurs seems to take it in stride.
Six Pappas children, all in their 20s and 30s, are involved in day-to-day operations. Christina handles marketing and guest relations while her sister Mary handles restaurant operations. Another sister, Evy, is an architect and oversees restaurant construction. Brother H.D. manages real estate interests and younger brother Tom just joined the business and is working at their newest concept, Pappas Meat Co. Chris' daughter Georgea heads up culinary research and development.
Mary literally grew up in the family business - at the time her dad and uncle took over the downtown restaurants, they were living in the 2016 Main apartment tower across the street. "My dad told all the employees he lived there so he could watch them all the time," Mary said.
After college, Mary started as a manager at a Pappadeaux location. Not long after that, Pappas acquired the Luther's Bar-B-Q chain and Mary oversaw its merger with Pappas. Although her background is in barbecue, Mary now oversees business operations for all Pappas restaurants.
Mary is quick to point out that Pappas still is a family-owned business; investors and shareholders aren't a factor in decision making. That's critical in the cyclical nature of the restaurant business. Whereas some chains will lay off employees and switch to lower quality ingredients to keep profits up during tough times, Pappas has the resources and the independence to ride out the slumps.
Many employees work for Pappas their whole lives, and two of the original employees hired by Chris and Harris Pappas still are involved with the company. Though there is a fast-track program for college graduates to become managers, almost all of their restaurant managers started as servers or cooks and all managers are promoted from within the company.
It all makes for consistency in management in a large restaurant chain. 
The new generation of the Pappas family is fully aware of the vagaries of the restaurant business, and the brutal competition they are sure to encounter in the future. 
"We like competition," Christina said. "It keeps us on our toes."









J.C. Reid

Columnist, Houston Chronicle


















 











